SQL Joins are used to retrieve data from multiple tables based on a related column.
INNER JOIN:
Returns only matching rows from both tables.
customers
| customer_id | name  |
| ----------- | ----- |
| 1           | Rahul |
| 2           | Anita |
| 3           | John  |
Orders
| order_id | customer_id |
| -------- | ----------- |
| 101      | 1           |
| 102      | 2           |
| 103      | 4           |

SELECT customers.name, orders.order_id
FROM customers
INNER JOIN orders
ON customers.customer_id = orders.customer_id;
output:
| name  | order_id |
| ----- | -------- |
| Rahul | 101      |
| Anita | 102      |
OUTER JOIN:
Outer joins return matching rows + non-matching rows.
LEFT OUTER JOIN:
Returns all rows from left table + matching rows from right table.
SELECT customers.name, orders.order_id
FROM customers
LEFT JOIN orders
ON customers.customer_id = orders.customer_id;
Output:
| name  | order_id |
| ----- | -------- |
| Rahul | 101      |
| Anita | 102      |
| John  | NULL     |
RIGHT OUTER JOIN:
Returns all rows from right table + matching rows from left table.
SELECT customers.name, orders.order_id
FROM customers
RIGHT JOIN orders
ON customers.customer_id = orders.customer_id;
| name  | order_id |
| ----- | -------- |
| Rahul | 101      |
| Anita | 102      |
| NULL  | 103      |
SELF JOIN:
A table joined with itself
Employees:
| emp_id | name | manager_id |
| ------ | ---- | ---------- |
| 1      | John | NULL       |
| 2      | Sam  | 1          |
| 3      | Rita | 1          |
SELECT e1.name AS employee, e2.name AS manager
FROM employees e1
LEFT JOIN employees e2
ON e1.manager_id = e2.emp_id;
Output:
| employee | manager |
| -------- | ------- |
| John     | NULL    |
| Sam      | John    |
| Rita     | John    |
SEMI JOIN:
A Semi Join returns rows from the first table where at least one matching row exists in the second table.
They are usually implemented using EXISTS / NOT EXISTS / IN / NOT IN.
It only checks existence, not duplicates.
Customers
| customer_id | name  |
| ----------- | ----- |
| 1           | Rahul |
| 2           | Anita |
| 3           | John  |
| 4           | Meena |
Orders
| order_id | customer_id |
| -------- | ----------- |
| 101      | 1           |
| 102      | 2           |
| 103      | 1           |
SELECT name
FROM customers c
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT 1
    FROM orders o
    WHERE o.customer_id = c.customer_id
);
SELECT name
FROM customers
WHERE customer_id IN (
    SELECT customer_id FROM orders
);
Output:
| name  |
| ----- |
| Rahul |
| Anita |
ANTI JOIN:
An Anti Join returns rows from the first table that do NOT have matching rows in the second table.
SELECT name
FROM customers c
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
    SELECT 1
    FROM orders o
    WHERE o.customer_id = c.customer_id
);
SELECT name
FROM customers
WHERE customer_id NOT IN (
    SELECT customer_id FROM orders
);
output:
| name  |
| ----- |
| John  |
| Meena |

SET OPERATORS:
student A
| student_id | name  |
| ---------- | ----- |
| 1          | Rahul |
| 2          | Anita |
| 3          | John  |
student B
| student_id | name  |
| ---------- | ----- |
| 3          | John  |
| 4          | Meena |
| 5          | David |

UNION:
Combines results and removes duplicates.
SELECT name FROM Students_A
UNION
SELECT name FROM Students_B;
Output:
| name  |
| ----- |
| Rahul |
| Anita |
| John  |
| Meena |
| David |

UNION ALL:
Combines results including duplicates.
SELECT name FROM Students_A
UNION ALL
SELECT name FROM Students_B;
Output:
| name  |
| ----- |
| Rahul |
| Anita |
| John  |
| John  |
| Meena |
| David |


INTERSECT
Returns common rows from both queries.
SELECT name FROM Students_A
INTERSECT
SELECT name FROM Students_B;
output:
| name |
| ---- |
| John |

MINUS :
Returns rows present in first query but not in second query.
SELECT name FROM Students_A
MINUS
SELECT name FROM Students_B;
output:
| name  |
| ----- |
| Rahul |
| Anita |

